To find the optimal control input $u$ that stabilizes the system around the equilibrium point $(x_1, x_2) = (0, 0)$, we can use the Linear Quadratic Regulator (LQR) approach from optimal control theory.

First, we linearize the system around the equilibrium point. The linearized system can be represented as:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\dot{x} = Ax + Bu
\end{aligned}
$$

where $x = \begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix}$, $A = \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ a & -b \end{bmatrix}$, and $B = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}$, with $a = 1$ and $b = 0.5$.

Next, we define a cost function to minimize. A common choice is the quadratic cost function:

$$
\begin{aligned}
J = \int_{0}^{\infty} (x^T Q x + u^T R u) dt
\end{aligned}
$$

where $Q$ and $R$ are positive definite matrices that weigh the importance of the state and control input, respectively. For simplicity, we can choose $Q = I$ and $R = 1$.

The LQR problem aims to find the optimal control input $u^*$ that minimizes the cost function $J$. The optimal control input can be represented as:

$$
\begin{aligned}
u^* = -Kx
\end{aligned}
$$

where $K$ is the optimal feedback gain matrix. The optimal gain matrix $K$ can be found by solving the Algebraic Riccati Equation (ARE):

$$
\begin{aligned}
0 = A^T P + PA - PBR^{-1}B^T P + Q
\end{aligned}
$$

where $P$ is a positive definite matrix.

In our case, we have:

$$
\begin{aligned}
A = \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 1 & -0.5 \end{bmatrix}, \quad B = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}, \quad Q = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix}, \quad R = 1
\end{aligned}
$$

Solving the ARE for $P$ and then finding the optimal gain matrix $K$:

$$
\begin{aligned}
K = R^{-1} B^T P = \begin{bmatrix} k_1 & k_2 \end{bmatrix}
\end{aligned}
$$

Finally, the optimal control input $u^*$ that stabilizes the system around the equilibrium point $(x_1, x_2) = (0, 0)$ is:

$$
\begin{aligned}
u^* = -Kx = -k_1 x_1 - k_2 x_2
\end{aligned}
$$

To find the specific values of $k_1$ and $k_2$, you can use numerical methods to solve the ARE and compute the optimal gain matrix $K$.
